If you call setVertices twice on the same Polygon instance, the second call will overwrite the vertex array used in the first call with the one from the second call if they're the same size.

Example:

float[] v1 = {1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 4.0f, 5.0f, 6.0f};
float[] v2 = {1.5f, 2.5f, 3.5f, 4.5f, 5.5f, 6.5f};

Polygon p1 = new Polygon();
p1.setVertices(v1);
p1.setVertices(v2);

This will cause the contents of v2 to overwrite v1.

This is useful for frameworks that want to be compatible across different versions of LibGdx.
For example if version 1.2.0 will fix an issue and you know a workaround for previous versions then in your code you can quickly do something like this 

``` java
if (Version.MAJOR == 1 && Version.MINOR < 2) {
   // Apply workaround
}
```

